{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659628"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:12:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:12:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20876"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20876"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13751"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96887"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13751"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20876"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79502"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"11592"},{"type":"tags","id":"11593"},{"type":"tags","id":"12699"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33114"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96887"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how mutations in noncoding DNA sequences can cause disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alteration of amino acid sequence in the protein","Activation of oncogene expression","Disruption of transcription factor binding sites","Creation of premature stop codons","Frameshift in the coding sequence"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Edisruption of transcription factor binding sites\u003C/strong\u003E. Mutations in noncoding regions, particularly in promoter and enhancer sequences, can interfere with the binding of transcription factors. This disruption can lead to reduced or completely absent transcription of the associated gene, resulting in decreased or absent protein production. In thalassemias, mutations in regulatory regions of globin genes lead to reduced globin chain synthesis, causing anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlteration of amino acid sequence in the protein\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs with mutations in exons (coding regions), not noncoding sequences. Noncoding mutations do not directly change the amino acid sequence.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of oncogene expression\u003C/strong\u003E - While some noncoding mutations can affect gene expression, this option is too specific and not the primary mechanism by which noncoding mutations typically cause disease.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreation of premature stop codons\u003C/strong\u003E - Stop codons are created by mutations within coding sequences (exons), not noncoding regions.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrameshift in the coding sequence\u003C/strong\u003E - Frameshift mutations occur when nucleotides are inserted or deleted within coding regions, not in noncoding sequences.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnother important mechanism by which noncoding mutations cause disease is through disruption of mRNA splicing. Mutations within introns can interfere with splice sites, preventing proper removal of introns during mRNA processing. This results in failure to form mature mRNA, preventing translation and protein synthesis. Both mechanisms (disruption of transcription factor binding and interference with splicing) represent ways that mutations in noncoding DNA can lead to pathological conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mutations in noncoding DNA sequences can cause disease by disrupting gene expression or RNA processing.","Mutations in promoter or enhancer regions can reduce or prevent transcription by interfering with transcription factor binding.","Intronic mutations can disrupt mRNA splicing, preventing the formation of mature mRNA for translation."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 142"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79502"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20876"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79502"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T12:14:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T12:15:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13751"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96887"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10763"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Genetic disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11592"},